          "correctOptionId": "opt-2",
          "explanation": "Xenon is Non- teratogenic.Option A: Xenon has a very low blood-gas solubility coefficient (0.115) and produces rapid induction of and emergence from anaesthesia.Option B: Xenon produces no green house effect or ozone depletion and is environmentally safe, unlike the other inhaled anaesthetics.Option D: Does not trigger malignant hypehermia Other advantages of xenon:IneMinimal cardiovascular effects- It produces minimal cardiovascular depression, and it is not arrhythmogenic.Non explosiveHas Analgesic activity - reduces intraoperative opioid requirements Disadvantages of Xenon High costLow potency (MAC = 70%)Xenon gas has a very high density (5.9 g/L) resulting in increased flow resistance and work of breathing. Thus, it may be a poor choice for patients wicompromised respiratory function",
          "hint": "Topic: Inhalational Anesthetic Agents"
